l possession, and that the perspective of ourselves as potential victims is an ineliminable feature of everyday moral experience.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthics. 0aRapexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aTorturexMoral and ethical aspects. 0aTrustxSocial aspects. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  atorture, dignity, pain, suffering, morality, ethics, dependence, interdependence, rape, trust, society, humanity, beccaria, rule of law, amerys, reason, emotion, sovereignty, self consciousness, recognition, necessity, nuremberg, treblinka, humiliation, devastation, alienation, respect, abolition, human rights, nonfiction, philosophy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022626632940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226266466423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226266466/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles